data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_070bf61096fef9430069a88aef50a0819580c86382e546edc3","logprobs":[],"output_index":10,"sequence_number":435,"text":"Kubernetes (often “K8s”) is an open-source system for **orchestrating containers**—scheduling them onto machines, scaling them, handling failures, networking, and rollouts.\n\n### Historical summary (key milestones)\n\n- **Roots at Google (pre-2014):** Kubernetes grew out of Google’s long experience running containers at massive scale, especially through internal cluster managers like **Borg** (and later Omega). Many Kubernetes design ideas—declarative desired state, automated scheduling, self-healing—reflect those lessons.\n\n- **Open-sourced by Google (2014):** Google released Kubernetes as an open-source project in **2014**, positioning it as a general, vendor-neutral way to run containerized workloads across clusters.\n\n- **Formation of a neutral governance home (2015):** To ensure Kubernetes wasn’t controlled by a single vendor and to accelerate industry adoption, Kubernetes was donated to the newly formed **Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF)** in **2015**. This helped create a broad ecosystem of contributors and companies around it.\n\n- **Rapid ecosystem growth (2016–2017):** Kubernetes became the de facto standard container orchestrator. Core features matured (deployments, services, ingress, RBAC, federation attempts, etc.), and a large “cloud native” tooling ecosystem formed around it (networking, observability, service meshes, operators).\n\n- **Project maturity / “graduation” (2018):** Kubernetes became the **first CNCF project to graduate** (a CNCF maturity milestone), signaling strong governance, widespread production use, and sustained community health.\n\n- **Mainstream platform layer (late 2010s–2020s):** Kubernetes evolved into a common “platform substrate” across clouds and on‑prem, with major cloud providers offering managed Kubernetes and enterprises standardizing on it for application delivery and infrastructure abstraction.\n\nIf you tell me whether you want a **high-level story** or a **timeline with versions and feature milestones**, I can tailor the summary."}

